  "slug": "cassata-siciliana",
  "title": "Cassata siciliana",
  "subtitle": "Sicilian sponge cake filled with ricotta and candied fruit",
  "excerpt": "A Sicilian celebration cake with a pan di spagna sponge filled with a sweet ricotta, candied fruit, and chocolate cream, encased in marzipan, and decorated with glossy fondant icing and more candied fruit. The assembly requires patience rather than complex technique: each component is simple, but the layers must be chilled between steps. The result is a very rich, sweet cake served in small slices.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Cassata siciliana has its origins in Arab-influenced Sicilian sweets from the medieval period and is documented in Sicilian and Italian culinary literature from at least the sixteenth century. Pellegrino Artusi, La Scienza in Cucina e l'Arte di Mangiar Bene (1891, freely available at Project Gutenberg IT), describes cassata as a Sicilian preparation. The layered sponge, ricotta, and marzipan format with fondant icing is described in Italian baking guides and Sicilian domestic manuals published before 1928.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cassata is a two-day cake. Bake the sponge and make the ricotta filling on day one, then assemble and refrigerate overnight. Decorate on day two. The ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "pan di spagna sponge",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "term": "Pan di spagna",
                  "termId": "cmppnl3wa0000i8v4k6gx0yza"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " must be cold before assembly. Chill the filled cake before the marzipan and icing go on.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
